@article{Tomasch1969,
   abstract = {The constituent nerve cells of the pontine griseum represent for all practical purposes an extrinsic cerebellar system. Its white matter consists of axons that enter the pons via the cerebral peduncle, and of the axons derived from the pontine nerve cells themselves. Of the former group, cortico-spinal and some cortico-bulbar fibers just traverse this region, the balance consisting of cortico-pontine fibers that relay at the pontine nerve cells. Although no quantitative information about the pontine complex is available, there are numerous published estimates of the number of axons that traverse the pons to congregate in the pyramid. These estimates center around a mean of 1 million axons for one side. The counting of axons in a section at the level of the pyramid is facilitated by the predominantly parallel course of the constituent fibers. Within the cerebral peduncle, however, fiber bundles that meander are frequently encountered. This pattern requires specialized statistical treatment when fiber densities are sampled over the cross-section of the cerebral peduncle. Owing to their wavy course, a considerable proportion of fiber groups is cut at oblique angles. MATERIAL AND METHODS The estimates presented in this paper are based on a section series of the brain stem of a 56-year-old male. The same section series was the subject of a number of already published quantitative studies carried out in our laboratory 5,7,s,1°,11. The griseum pontis extends into 1125 sections 25/t thick. Alternate sections were stained by the methods of H~iggqvist and Weigert. One section at the mid-pontine level was used in a field-by-field cell count. The figure of 23,653 cells obtained by counting could be approximated consistently to within ± 5.7 ~ by the sampling of nucleoli in 100 fields chosen at random, each field covering a cross-sectional area of 62,500 sq./~. When the results of the estimation procedure are weighted with 0.1, the},
